## Noun Cases\
\
### Genitive Cases\
\
In **Verbum**, when a proper noun is used it is spelled how the original language sounds, just like with animals, and the Proper Name prefix (**g\uc0\u363 -**) is added to let the listener know that should the following word have a definition in **Verbum**, it is to be interpreted as a person, place, of thing\'92s name. When referring to the genitive case in a sentence construction, the proper name will precede the possessive item. The possessive morpheme (**m\u275 -**) is then added to the possessed item. For example:\
\
Proper Name \'96 _Stacy_ (English), **g\uc0\u363 st\u257 s\u275 ** \
\
Possessive \'96 _Stacy\'92s Mom_ (English), **g\uc0\u363 st\u257 s\u275  m\u275 monow\u257 ** \
\
